  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 7
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 7
  levelTerms:
  - level: 27
    terms:
    - term: Gravity
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: It is present in tides, celestial mechanics, and potential energy
      details: 'It was Isaac Newton, and his story was somewhat of a flamboyant version
        of what happened, which was almost lost in history. Still, his ideas, along
        with a few other natural philosophers (scientists in the modern age), have
        helped shape our understanding of Physics.

'
    - term: 'Gravitational Force '
      unit: F_g
      type: 2
      description: Responsible for giving us Newtonian weight (F_g = Weight)
      details: "The force of gravity (Fg). It is responsible for giving us our Newtonian
        weight (Fg = Weight), which is calculated through the constant, g.\n\nGravitational
        Potential Energy:\nU_g = mgy\n\nForce of Gravity:\nF_g = G \u2022 ((m_1 \u2022
        m_2) / r\xB2)\n\nEscape Velocity:\nv_e = \u221A2Gm/r"
  - level: 29
    terms:
    - term: "Kepler\u2019s Laws of Planetary Motion"
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Theory and computations proven by Johannes Kepler, a mathematician
        helping Tycho Brahe in his astronomical research
      details: "As theorized by Newton, planets and other celestial bodies have their
        paths shaped like conic sections. This theory was eventually proven by Johannes
        Kepler, a mathematician who helped the astronomer Tycho Brahe in his astronomical
        research. Kepler\u2019s calculations. His computations are named by astronomers
        as \u201CKepler\u2019s Laws of Planetary Motion\u201D.\r\n"
    - term: The Law of Elliptical Orbits
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: All orbital paths of planets take on an elliptical shape, with
        the sun as one of its focus
      details: 'Also known as the Law of Ellipses, it states that all orbital paths
        of planets take on an elliptical shape, with the Sun as one of its focus.
        If we are to recall our geometry, an ellipse is a conic section wherein it
        has foci located in its semi major axis. You can check the diagram on the
        next page.

'
    - term: The Law of Equal Areas
      unit: 
      type: 0
      description: Aphelion - farthest point of a planet from the sun, creating a
        very narrow "pizza slice"
      details: "This states that all calculated areas, which result from a planet\u2019s
        movement around the Sun, are all equal in values.\n\nThis is best explained
        by the astronomical terms perihelion and aphelion. Perihelion is the period
        of a planet wherein it is close to the Sun, thus creates a very wide triangle,
        or \u201Cpizza slice\u201D, colloquially. "
    - term: The Law of Harmonies
      unit: 
      type: 2
      description: The ratio of the squares of the planets' periods (T) is equal
        to the ratio of the cubes of planet's average distance (r) from the Sun
      details: "This law states that, by observing the motions of two planets moving
        around the Sun, therein lies a \r\ncalculated ratio where the ratio of the
        squares of the planets\u2019 periods (T) is equal to the ratio of the cubes
        of the planets\u2019 average distances (r) from the Sun. In Mathematical
        terms,\n\nThe Law of Harmonies:\nT_1\xB2/T_2\xB2 = r_1\xB2/r_2\xB2\r\n"
